  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Applet Structure**\n\nI\'m now contemplating the architecture of this Applet. It seems like it will include a custom Express server (`server.ts`) for the backend, managing the `/api/generate` calls. However, I\'m thinking about the client-side interaction in a native Android application and if this implementation is ideal.\n\n\n**Analyzing Backend Integration**\n\nI\'ve realized a critical point: the Android app, essentially the web build within a WebView, must communicate with our hosted server, not a local one. Relative API requests like `/api/generate` will fail in a mobile context. Therefore, I\'m considering implementing an absolute backend URL fallback for mobile environments to ensure proper API communication when the app is packaged.\n\n\n**Determining Mobile Fetch Logic**\n\nI\'m now determining how best to handle fetch requests in a mobile/native context. The key is adapting the API server URL. I\'m considering using environment variables, auto-detection of the protocol based on `window.location`, and even the deployed container\'s URL. The development URL is `https://ais-dev-datlpi4psyrf5dauco7nts-38127143829.us-east1.run.app`, and the shared production URL is likely something like `https://ais-pre-datlpi4psyrf5dauco7nts-38127143829.us-east1.run.app`. I\'m evaluating making the fetch logic smart, falling back if the current page isn\'t using a standard HTTP protocol. Let me find the fetch implementation in `/src/App.tsx`.\n\n\n"
